  "doc_id": "20181",
  "text": "Practically all biological processes are pH-dependent and pH is an important regulator of cellular function. Different compartments of the cell have different characteristic pH (see reviews 99100, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ). Macromolecules that shuttle between different cellular compartments, as for example, prolactin receptor, 102; 103 have their pH-dependent characteristics precisely tuned to the local pH. Thus, in order to function properly and interact with its biological partners, the protein needs maintain specific pH dependent characteristics 22 which can be very sensitive to single point mutations. [CITATION_3] In addition, single point mutations may affect a protein's cellular location. [CITATION_4] More examples are provided in Table 3 .",
